<dl id="n08099k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08099k">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08099k"> 99(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> I mean to &mdash; pro-infinitive</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Another recent innovation is the use of <i>to</i> as what might be called a pro-infinitive instead of the clumsy <i>to do so</i>: &lsquo;Will you play?&rsquo; &lsquo;Yes, I intend to.&rsquo; <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 203 [Split Infinitive]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
